segments.text: Apollo Soyuz.
Apollo Soyuz.
Yeah.
We've been told the benefits, mostly in a diplomatic sense.
What impact do you really think they had diplomatically in 1975?
Well, I think it had a lot of diplomatic impact on...
in the Soviet Union.
They played it up much more than we did here.
And I think that the only way that you ever change attitudes is in Russia.
is sort of everybody together, long-term, or no single big event.
You know, that's not true.
No, it just takes time to change people's attitudes, and particularly to make them more friendly.
You can make them an enemy real quick by doing something bad to them, but to make them friendly takes a long, long time,
And it's just a matter of continuing to be friendly towards them and to do things towards them that they perceive as friendly.
And so it takes a lot of effort.
And you just have to go ahead and make the investment realizing that...
that you're not going to just get an instant reward.
And somebody said, Machiavelli or somebody said that in matters of importance, you can't hope to sow and reap at the same time.
And that's a case like the Russian.
You can't hope to reap all the friendship.
You can only sow and then sow again in another year or two and then continue to sow good deeds and hopefully someday you can reap the benefits.
But you can't be disappointed because you don't reap them initially because you're just not.
It's not the way of the world, I don't think.
You're talking like we haven't reaped the benefits yet.
Or maybe we have a little bit.

But I think that we ought to jump at the chance to do that because being friends with them is so much better than fighting them that you ought to just, any chance, if they came up and said, well, let's have this little get-together and do this and this, if there's any way we could do it with not jeopardizing our own defense posture or something like that, we ought to go do it.
I mean, we ought to do everything we can to up the trade with them and to exchange non-military things with them and...
to try to be friendly because you want to end up being friends with those people.
You don't want to fight them.
You just have to, you know, in order to be friendly, you've got to be friendly.
So I think it was really good, but I don't think we could look for any benefit at the moment.
It's more of a long-term kind of thing.
Did you see any negative things come out of it?
I didn't see any negative things.
I think we taught them a lot that's helped them make their space program better.

In other words, I think the thing that we taught them was generally an attitude about man in space can do things and to go ahead and try it, try to repair it on orbit, try to figure ways to make things work where they never seemed to have that attitude before.
So I think they gained a tremendous benefit from that
I don't feel that we gained much of a benefit, because we were so far ahead of them in all these areas, that we're going to have to look to increased friendship as the benefit, which they can too.
We've gone more than halfway, but I think that you want to go more than halfway if you have to.
I mean, even if you have to go 90% of the way, eventually if it leads to friendship...
Go the 90%, you know, it's worth it.
So I'm glad we did it, and I think we ought to do it if we have another chance.
Okay, the Soviet Union has taken foreign nationals in space with them.
Yeah.
Why do you think the U.S. has not done that in the past?
I don't think...
I don't think it would be a nice thing to do.
However, I don't think anybody perceived it as nice a thing to do as just doing the job we had to do.
For example, I don't know if France would like us better if we took a Frenchman in space or not.
I think we'd eventually do it.
But, and I think with Space Shuttle we ought to try to include multinational crews and things.
But before we've been trying to do certain scientific things and although we could have done it with foreign nationals, it was easier to do it and not worry about that part of the problem.
And I don't know if it would have,
helped us anymore.
You know, these things are helpful, but they're long-term helpful.
I guess we'll end up taking some Frenchmen, because we have some in the space lab.
Claude Nicollier, nice guy.
He's really Swiss.
So I don't know.
I guess we could have.
We just didn't put that as a high priority.
It's sort of like we probably could have found...
a black person that knew enough, that knew enough flying or something to go to the moon.
But it was, the best qualified people we had weren't, so we didn't do that.
But we could have, I mean, you could have put a black person in the right seat of any lunar mission, I think you'd have been just as successful as it was.
But I guess we didn't worry about that so much as trying to get the best qualified people we knew.
You know, almost speaking of NASA, I don't know, it's early years, it's being self-centered.
Like, you know, in its own organization, do you think we're basically just concerned with our own interests in our own program and not necessarily?
Apollo Soyuz was a...
an open gesture.
But besides that, would you say it's mostly been closed within itself?
Well, I...
I don't think of it exactly the same way you said it there.
I think that NASA is charged with doing certain things in space for the government, you know.
And as a result...
And no one else is charged to do those things.
So I think you then begin to think on how you're going to do them for the government.
I mean, you know that you work for Congress and the president, but still your job is to do such and such in the best way.
And so...
you do tend to get to be a closed unit because you're the ones that are working on it and thinking about it.
Not very many other people are.
For example, those of us in NASA aren't wondering whether or not they ought to build additional Trident submarines.
I mean, we're not qualified to say.
We don't do studies on it.
And we're counting on the people that Congress has appointed in charge of the Navy to do that part of the job.
It's a little bit like a football team.
You kind of know what the other people are doing, but you've got a certain man to block or you've got to run out for a pass.
And if you're supposed to run out for a pass, you better not worry about what the other guy's doing so much is trying to do your job.
If you can do your job and help him, that's great.
But generally, you know, you have to do your own job.
And our job was exploration of space, so I guess we tended to concentrate on that.
And...
I didn't see us as closed, other than just the fact that we were the only people working on the job.
We weren't trying to keep anybody out.
Okay, along with the space shuttle, do you see any reasons that it didn't meet its original time schedule, the projected time schedule, other than the monetary problems that it involved?
Well, yeah, I think probably that the people that were making the decisions realized that it was going to take longer and more money to do the shuttle than they could sell the program on.
And so they said, let's be as optimistic as we can.
Let's don't be dishonest and lie, but what...
What is the earliest we can do it?
What's the cheapest we can do it?
I mean, think cheap, think soon.
And you know, when you start doing things like that, you can convince yourself that things could happen pretty quick, pretty cheap.
And be honest, you know, honest.
Because it's just a guess, an educated guess.
I mean, it's more than just sitting here guessing, but it's still a guess, just with more details.
So I think they tried to guess on the short side because it was more palatable.
It's like the president right now, playing like he didn't know there was going to be a recession.
At the same time, he was going to stop inflation.
I mean, how was he going to do it?
If he didn't put people out of work, how was he going to keep people from spending money?
I mean, it's like...
You've got to have one without the other.
He's going to give them more money and hope they don't spend more and thus make more inflation?
I mean, it doesn't make sense.
The only way that he can stop inflation is to get a recession and cut people's money off.
Then they don't have money to spend, and then the prices come down.
But you notice he never says that.
He never says, look, I knew this was going to be this way.
Do you know any other way to stop people from spending money other than cut their money off?
I mean, he never says it that way.
But, you know, he's got to know it.
I mean, he's dumb.
And so I think what occurred was
was there was this optimistic estimate, because I don't think we really ran into any more unknown problems than we would expect.
We had trouble with the tiles and the engines.
But in a big development program like that, you know you're going to have trouble with something, so maybe we didn't know it was those two things.
However, we knew two or three things would pop up.

so i think more it's more of and probably when they allowed time they didn't allow time to solve those because they congress wanted something happening i mean you know the car dealer saying man we can get your new car in six weeks six weeks later they're telling you it ought to be in any day and it really comes in and
In ten weeks, and they knew all along it was going to be ten weeks.
Now, they had a couple come in in six weeks.
But generally, it's ten weeks.
But they never tell you ten weeks because you don't want to hear it.
You want to hear six weeks.
Because if you don't, you go to the other dealer and they tell you six weeks.
You buy from them.
So, it's just the way of the world.
It's one of the reasons I don't want to do any of that sort of thing.
I don't want to be part of that kind of thing.
I don't want to tell Congress something like that.
What is NASA's plans after the space show?
I think NASA's plans, as soon as we get it going and try to get a lot of paying customers, then begin to start constructing some sort of space station.
And I think this will happen

uh... within ten years because we'll have all the elements and we can build space stations not cheap but not anywhere like it cost to go in apollo or to build a space shuttle so uh... i look for uh... some sort of new start here in another four years let's say when reagan gets let's say if reagan were re-elected

then he would know it was his last term by then he would start to have the economy under control I think and when he did then he would be looking for something like this to help the economy and to help progress and if he's the kind of person Reagan is strikes me as the kind of man that would
He's very much interested in research and development and keeping a good defense.
He seems like a person that's not just doing something for today.
He's trying to get the Social Security thing on a paying basis.
He was recently voted down by a bunch of congressmen that know damn well that it ain't going to float if they voted it, and they still voted it.
So he seems to have more guts.
So my guess is he'll want the space program to enlarge, but he can't do it now because of the money.
What about any unmanned plans, just continuation of exploration of our planet?
That, just like that, and try to get some little programs so that people won't lose interest.
But his biggest problem is the economy and defense.
And so as a result of that, even though he might want to do these, he can't.
He's caught in a terrible situation where people have left him with lots of debts.
You know, all these debts, it's like somebody... What's occurred here is like my parents and me partly, in a way, have run up tremendous credit card debts
We just lived high, you know, and bought all sorts of stuff.
Right now, you and me too at the end, but your generation, somebody's got to pay the debts.
I mean, somebody's got to pay for the new car, figuratively speaking, my parents got that couldn't afford...
Somebody's got to pay for it.
Sooner or later, the guy comes around, okay?
And the story about, you know, we're all just borrowing from each other doesn't work because people borrow from each other, but you still got to pay it back.
So that's what happened.
The people of last generation, our generation, have lived way beyond their means and run it up on a credit card, the tune of a trillion bucks.
And sooner or later, you got to pay because the guys that owe the money to want to be paid.
And they left that with Reagan, and he's not even paying off the debt, you know.
He's just trying to service the interest.
Can you imagine what our life would be like if we had to spend more money per year than we made to live and pay the interest on our debt?
I mean, it wouldn't work as an individual at all.
It doesn't work as a country either.
But that's what's occurred, and so it's just tough on him.
But at least he's trying.
How do you assess the pluses and minuses of your whole career?
Hadn't been any minuses.
Hadn't been many minuses, no.
So it was all worth it?
Oh, yeah, it was all worth it.
It was great.
I had a lot of heartaches because I didn't maybe fly on Gemini and want to, but then it turned out okay.
No, I would...
At the time, you know, I may wanted to do this or do that and didn't get to do it.
But all in all, it just was a wonderful adventure.
And I was lucky and got to make two flights.
But I mean, even if only got to make one, it would be worth it.
I mean, if I'd only made one flight, I would still give you the same answer.
And it's also, when you're waiting, you're not just standing around the room waiting.
I mean, you're doing things that are interesting.
And also, you're educating yourself in a lot of things.
And the opportunities for learning things and all the things that went along with the space program could never, ever be gained anywhere else.
And so I...
If I had to give the rest of my life for it, you know, stay in NASA and be repetitive, let's say train new astronauts over and over again, it would definitely be worth it.
I don't have to do it, which is just luck, and I can go off and start a brand new career that I like.
But...
No, I can't think of a negative.
At the time, they seemed it.
And certainly I could invent a career that was better.
I mean, I could have flown a couple of flights in Gemini, and then I could have made the first lunar landing instead of Neil.
I mean, I could have done a lot of other stuff that would have been even more fantastic.
But, you know, you don't really expect that.
You just expect...
You just can't hardly expect to do more and have a happier 18 years than what would I do that was better.
I gave you some examples, but you really can't expect them.
You've got to be happy with what comes along.
How do you think being an astronaut affects, not necessarily you personally, but basically being an astronaut affects those men's later lives?
gives them a great freedom to be like they really are.
And so it satisfies the need to be famous or recognized or somebody saying you're a good person, you know, or you're brave or something, which men like.
And so it satisfies that.
And then once it's satisfied...
then it lets you go beyond it.
Whereas if that's not satisfied, I don't think you can go beyond it.
It's a little bit like mounting a hill or a mountain.
Unless you mount those hills of being famous, worthy, and all that, you can't ever get beyond them.
And so I think what it does is it lets people go beyond that.
It lets them get to the top, they see that, and then they...
They can climb another one higher if that's what they want.
Or they can go down and do something else.
But it's a great thing for your personal life because it fills an incredible square in your life that you've always wanted to fill.
And if you don't,
will have, I think, a detrimental effect.
So I think it couldn't be better.
I mean, it just couldn't be.
Now, I think you've got to go in with the attitude that a lot of this is out of your control.
And so you're going to tend to accept what you get as good.
You know what I mean?
I mean, like I said, I gave you a career that was a lot better than mine, okay?
But I...

if i couldn't be happy with the one i had it'd be something wrong with me i mean that's the same way with everybody that flew i mean if they couldn't be happy with the career they had there's something wrong because we had the very best thing you could have and if everybody's got to be neil armstrong something's wrong i mean you got to get a better attitude
you've got to get an attitude that what you get out of it, you like, because the opportunities were there for so much other than just the flying.
I mean, you got to meet a lot of people.
And really, one of the things I liked the best was I did.
I got to meet a lot of people that were successful or famous or rich or a lot of other things.
And you really, then you can look around and sort of decide,

with the knowledge instead of wondering what it's like you can see what it's like and then you can decide for your own life what you're going to do with it whereas maybe if maybe for example you didn't see how rich people lived in the life they have you would always want that life you still might you might want to eat more but by seeing it then you can make a more educated judgment unto what you want to do so being an astronaut lets you look at all the options available in life

and then you could pick the one you wanted to go for, like your dad did, or I did, or somebody else, and be content to, and not really be going this way, and wish you were going that way, and a lot of people never get here, because they also want to go back over here, and you can't go both places, and they go this way, and then they go this way, and then this way, and they never really just say, this is better, and I realize I'm giving up a lot of here, and I'm just going to go that way, and
If I get here and didn't want to go there, then I'll come back.
But I'll never get here unless I go there and I realize that by going here, I can't go there simultaneously.
So there's an old story that a ship is a very lucky thing because it can only go to one destination at a time.
But if you look at the history of a ship, then it goes lots of places.
But if people were like that, they'd be much better off too because then they can go.
Because they can only go one place at a time, but they don't know it.
And so they go like this, and they really want to go here, here, or here, and they spend their life doing this, and finally they say to hell with it, I can't make it.
And really, they could have gone just like this with a lot less trouble.
So I think NASA helps a lot.
It's one of the luckiest things to ever happen to anyone.
